headline.main: Shuttle Returns to Earth With a Special Passenger

results.snippet: The Endeavour brought back the first Japanese astronaut to have engaged in long-duration orbit.
results.lead_paragraph: The shuttle Endeavour closed out a grueling 16-day space station assembly mission with a smooth landing here Friday, bringing back to Earth, after four and a half months, the first Japanese astronaut to have engaged in long-duration orbit. With the shuttle approaching from the south after a computer-orchestrated descent, the mission commander, Mark L. Polansky, took over manual control 50,000 feet above the Florida spaceport, banked to line up on Runway 15 and guided the 110-ton craft to a picture-perfect touchdown at 10:48 a.m., Eastern time.

headline.kicker: A Conversation With Paul Root Wolpe
headline.main: A CONVERSATION WITH PAUL ROOT WOLPE

results.snippet: Paul Root Wolpe is a medical sociologist and bioethicist who directs the Center for Ethics at Emory University and is the first chief of bioethics for NASA.
results.lead_paragraph: Q. AS NASA'S CHIEF BIOETHICIST, WHAT DOES YOUR WORK INVOLVE? A. I'm an adviser to the chief medical officer for the agency. I don't make decisions. Instead, I analyze situations and policies and offer bioethical perspectives on specific problems.

results.abstract: NASA panel is grappling with cost-related issues as it prepares report to Obama administration on options for manned spaceflight; former astronaut Sally Ride has told panel that United States cannot send humans anywhere beyond International Space Station without spending more money; options under consideration by panel include extending space station's life beyond its planned 2010 retirement (M)

headline.main: NASA Panel Grapples With Cost of Space Plans

results.snippet: A committee convened by NASA is weighing the feasibility of space missions that include Moon bases, touring asteroids and landing on Mars.
results.lead_paragraph: The United States cannot afford to send humans anywhere beyond the space station -- especially Mars -- unless it wants to spend more money. ''You just can't get there,'' Sally Ride, the former astronaut, said over and over again on Wednesday as she presented calculations of the costs and timetables of various proposed space missions, ranging from establishing a base on the Moon to touring asteroids to landing on Mars.

headline.main: Obama To Speak at Cronkite Memorial

results.snippet: President Obama will be among the guest speakers at a public memorial service for Walter Cronkite next month, The Associated Press reported. The White House confirmed to The A.P. that the president would speak at the event, scheduled for Sept. 9 at...
results.lead_paragraph: President Obama will be among the guest speakers at a public memorial service for Walter Cronkite next month, The Associated Press reported. The White House confirmed to The A.P. that the president would speak at the event, scheduled for Sept. 9 at Lincoln Center, in honor of Mr. Cronkite, below, the longtime CBS News anchorman who died on July 17. A full lineup for the service has not been announced, but a CBS executive told The A.P. that former President Bill Clinton is expected to attend, as well as Katie Couric, Andy Rooney and Bob Schieffer of CBS News; Tom Brokaw, the former NBC news anchor; and Buzz Aldrin, the former astronaut. Expected performers include Mickey Hart, Wynton Marsalis, Michael Feinstein, Jimmy Buffettand the Marine Corps band. Ticket information has not been announced.

headline.main: Discovery Lifts Off for Space Station

results.snippet: After three launch delays, the space shuttle Discovery thundered to life on a 13-day mission to deliver critical supplies and equipment to the International Space Station.
results.lead_paragraph: Lighting up the midnight sky, the space shuttle Discovery finally thundered to life late Friday after three launch delays and rocketed away on a 13-day mission to deliver critical supplies and equipment to the International Space Station. Running four days late because of bad weather and trouble with a hydrogen valve in the shuttle's engine compartment, Discovery's two solid-fuel boosters ignited with a crackling roar at 11:59 p.m., instantly pushing the spacecraft away from launch pad 39A atop twin torrents of 5,000-degree flame.
